history.text: Hey, did you see Morten Tyldum's new film?
The recent one from 2014.
Yes its loosely based on the bigraphy of Alan turing.
I don't usually like biopics but Imitation Game was pretty good!
Benedict Cumberbatch was a knockout in that role!
What did you think of Keira Knightley as Joan Clarke?
Benedict Cumberbatch was great I agree
Keira Knightly was great in this thriller.
I love movies based during ww2
Agreed.  Even though some people felt they took too much artistic license, I still thought they did a good job capturing Turing's bravery.
Yes it did take liberties with its source material
It did but you cannot deny that it's pretty undeniably strong in its portrayal of Turing.
Yes and the code decryption scenes were intense.
The BBC drama Breaking the code also touches on the subject of this movie.
I believe its an instant classic.
Yeah, it did get a lot of critical acclaim and was being hailed as one of the greatest movies of 2014.
The scene where Christopher dies before Alan can tell him he loves him broke my heart!
The scenes from Turing's boarding school were great
So sad his friend died.
Yeah, it's crazy to think all that happened in the 1920s.

The Enigma machine is something  alright.

So many cryptographers working to crack a code.  It's impressive.
It is sweet he named his machine after Christopher.  That's love right there.
I was surprised Turing proposed to Clarke to keep her working with him.
It must have been so hard keeping his homosexuality a secret.
Yes for sure at that time it had to be kept secret.

Definitely.  There were a lot of secrets to keep - especially about having cracked the code.
\

Yeah and to think that Cairncross was a Soviet Spy!! I did not see that coming!
Right and him threatening to tell people about Turrng's homosexuality was low.
It was.  And it didn't even matter in the end!  Menzes already knew and was working with him!
I felt sorry for Clarke when Turing sent her away and told her he was gay.
He was just trying to keep her safe.

they had to destroy all thier work  after the war it
